# ASC documentation `$` notation

When writing or editing **documentation** in this repo (living docs, changelogs, plans, READMEs, rules prose):

## Meaning (locked)

- Any `$`-prefixed name means **"any make entry point"** (e.g. `$subject`, `$action`, `$object`, `$field.able.subject`).
- This is **documentation notation only** — **not** on-disk file names and **not** a requirement to put `$` in paths.
- Purpose: precise shared vocabulary so everyone names the same operable surface the same way.

## Exception — `$subject` (only)

`$subject` is the **only** exception to the usual `$`-prefixed doc notation above. It **can** be:

- plain **slugified string** values (like any var or function name), **or**
- in the case of `*.hook.yml` or `*.hook.sh`, our **custom DSL notation**

All other `$`-prefixed doc names keep the general rule (any make entry point; docs notation only — not filenames).

## Locked relation forms (always with `$`)

```text
($field.able.subject)--($field.able.object)
($triple.able.subject)--($triple.able.predicate)--($triple.able.object)
```

Map via `$action.able.yml` → `$subject.$action`.

## Do not write (superseded)

- `(field.able.subject)--(field.able.object)` — missing `$`
- `(triple.able.subject)--(triple.able.predicate)--(triple.able.object)` — missing `$`
- Bare `--` / `--relation--` / `triple.predicate` without `.able`

## Common placeholders

Prefer `$subject`, `$action`, `$object`, `$field…`, `$triple…`, `$ASC_SHELL`, `$action.able.yml` over vague “the subject/action” when referring to make entry points.

